##Epidemic Diary: an ordinary person's epidemic life | Weisike epidemic topic

Micro-signal wethinker 2016

Cross-border thinking, international perspectives, collaborative exploration, and sharing of new knowledge.

_

Introduction:
After the Wuhan Epidemic, affects the human heart. It is the most serious public health event in China since SARS and an unforgettable memory for our generation. During the epidemic, Weisike will open the "epidemic" topic, invited experts and readers to contribute, we will regularly update quality manuscripts, these records will become a witness to history.

The author of today's post is a former member of Weisike and would like to share his experience with you. Hope can let more people hear the Voice of Common People!

_
_
_
_

Author | | a normal person | 

I'm one of the people in this part of the country, who seems to be the furthest away from the epidemic: I've never been to Hubei, I live in the north, I have no friends in Wuhan, and I've known about the epidemic a little since January 20.
But there are eggs under the nest, and I want to record the now insignificant experience for everyone involved in 2020.
At the end of December, when my friend and I were planning to go to South Korea for the New Year, my mother sent an online post saying that Wuhan had SARS.

We stayed in Korea for a week or so and returned home. No one in Beijing Capital International Airport wears a mask, and the crowds are a harbinger of the coming Spring Festival travel rush. We are still planning to go to the soup on the weekend, and even want to see a talk show before we leave Beijing.
Fortunately, because of the busy work, all did not come to pass. At that time the biggest news or the Forbidden City big G, eat melon on-line shopping for new year, brush to the mask flash purchase, but compared to nuts, "mask" how can it be a necessity for New Year.
Things changed on January 20, when the news broke about the Wuhan outbreak, and my mother called me to make sure I wore a mask outside. I remembered that the blue surgical mask she left for me last year had all been thrown away when we moved, so we had to go to the drugstore first to buy a mask. It seems that only then did we begin to realize the seriousness of the problem. The pharmacies in Beijing's Sixth Ring Road were out of stock overnight, i navigated to a small drugstore in the middle of nowhere, and the clerk said it was the only one available:
A few "n95s" , unmarked and unwrapped, lay loose on the table, and I turned away. At that time, how can you think, this three-nil products will not be able to buy it?
I started buying the N95 online, and I didn't have enough information to buy the 3M 1860, which I didn't have. Some of them were still selling Honeyville's anti-smog series at that time. I looked at the price. Normally, they sold 25 of them for 99 yuan. They sold them for 160 yuan. "To raise prices, the state will take care of them. " It turned out to be the thoughts of my then 26-year-old mind, it's really not a few dollars, just feel "trust XX will make prices back to normal" , so I did not buy those masks.

On the night of January 22nd, things took a turn for the worse. I bought some N95s from my colleagues at work and plan to use them when I take the train home in the evening. There was another incident: I caught an uber from work, and the driver was coughing and not wearing a mask. I was too embarrassed to ask him to put a mask on, but I asked him to open all the windows and pray for air to keep me safe.
My friend was going to take me to the train station, and we had a Haidilao dinner. The waiter wasn't wearing a mask, and I said, when are you coming home? The waiter said there would be no rest during the Spring Festival.
After dinner, we had nowhere to go that night and just walked around and around the street. After a few bars closed, a few foreigners in masks emerged from a Mexican restaurant in Sanlitun, their suitcases in tow, as if the world were ending.

It was parked at a 24-hour convenience store, and the clerk was the only one working. I walked around the tiny shop without a mask, but there was disinfectant, and I bought only the drinks and snacks I needed on the train.

In the early hours of the morning, we head to Beijing South Railway Station's deserted streets, wondering whether it was the homecoming or the terrifying news. The road went straight ahead, as if to a black hole-like future.

At the train station, I did not dare to stay in the waiting room, two people stay in the car until my ticket is ready to go out. It wasn't until I got on the train that I had a sense of reality: I was going home, I only had a mask, and I felt like a hero dying.

Masked passengers wait in the Waiting Hall of Wuhan Railway Station. (Source: China News Service)

Sleepless night, repeatedly brush the news, confusion and robbed a few days cat supermarket mask, think everything is fine.

When my father came to pick me up in the morning, I ordered him to keep his mask on. I don't want any 1% chance. Back home, my mother did not give me disinfection, can not help but hug me. We don't know how serious this is, how the virus will spread, how little information there is.

Makeup bag put in the foundation liquid, before I left, also want to see a friend on the New Year's Day to see a movie. I didn't realize I'd be home for 15 days.

I am this time the smallest existence, and Hubei is extremely remote. The last time, only my intern was from Wuhan, he returned his ticket home on January 20. He had originally transferred to his grandmother's home in Chongqing for the Spring Festival, but in the end he had to spend the Spring Festival in Beijing alone. The New Year's Eve dinner was noodles cooked by himself, watching the Glittering Days in a group House and worrying about your family back home.
A friend from Chongqing also stayed in Beijing, buying a bag of quick-frozen dumplings for New Year's Eve dinner at Youxian. On January 23, she reluctantly returned the plane ticket, the next day out of the policy refund free of charge.

The first few days in my hometown, by minus 30 degrees weather cold a little cold, my mother affixed to my forehead, and my father silently how to do. I turned and prayed that there wasn't even a chance.

The company quickly issued a decision to delay the start of work, from the 3rd to the 10th, to the pending. The situation in Beijing is worse than expected. No one knows when to stop, just like no one knows why it started, how it really started, and why it's come to this.

Because truth tellers are criticized and need to borrow a ladder to get to the truth. People jumping off bridges in despair, people chasing hearses to call for their mothers, people dying at their posts, people whose families have all been infected, people banging gongs on balconies... As a footnote to this great era, will eventually be forgotten, and will be forgotten again and again.

I've always felt that you shouldn't use someone else's misfortune to foil your own. But a casual expression of compassion can be cruel. I can only imagine how helpless it would be in that city, inside every closed unit door, out of the way, if death were invisible.

This helplessness spreads to 1.4 billion people, and the burden of sharing is so heavy. Several vendors said the government had requisitioned masks so they couldn't ship them; that they couldn't buy disinfectants, that they couldn't buy goggles:. .. The media sometimes said that this is useful, sometimes said that it is also necessary, like a drowning person, like grasping a straw, is even Shuanghuanglian.

That day, my colleagues in the work group sent out an article in the People's Daily, and I immediately rushed to buy Shuanghuanglian. I even felt a sense of luck: I got my first "supplies" . Later, my friend laughed at me for a long time. She thought that an educated person like me could be fooled by "rumors" .

But really have no choice, at that time, see People's Daily, in Taobao to see all sold out, you may be hard to control yourself, you do not want to miss out, in fact, you say I do not want to die.

It is the opinion of the most common man, and exploitation is a necessary consequence. The next day I returned all the double Coptis.

After what happened, I thought, "is this virus scary? "? Is it GONNA be dead in the next 24 hours? Not According to all the studies. But why are we so afraid? Why is our neighborhood closed?

IS OF UNKNOWN ORIGIN:

You don't know who you're walking into, does he know he's out there with the virus.
You don't know if you'll have basic security when you're quarantined, whether you get 60 cents for cabbage or 60 yuan.
You don't know if you're sick, if you have the resources, if you can get a bed at the hospital.
You don't know what's going to happen in your life in the meantime, whether it's a physical reaction to the treatment, or whether the virus is going to destroy you.
Yes, some of the questions were answered in the news, but is it true? Really? As a normal person, I open CCTV13 every day, but everything they say, I doubt it.

Is it true about the numbers that come out every day? Or "planned" to diagnose, suspect, and die.
The panel's words and the People's Daily's words, who are the rumors?
The train ticket and resumption of work policy, changing again and again, who decided to refund free, who will suddenly issued a delayed decision? What kind of person is in charge of the overall situation? When can I buy a mask? Why do people who tell the truth die? And why Wechat, Weibo, "can not view" ? What's Okay and what's not?

Well, right now, a lot of people want answers.
